deck_excerpt: I Got Iron in My Dino DNA!
deck_description: Dino is a deck made up of an amalgamation of Dinosaur-Type monsters originally made for OTK'ing your opponent, it has made a development in recent years to be able to go first, however it can still OTK.  For the decklist, we have a Dino package of 2x UCT, 2x Overtex, 1x Giant Rex, 3x Miscellaneousaurus, 3x Oviraptor, 3x Babycerasaurus, 3x Petiteranodon, 2x Archosaur, 3x Lost World(and 1x Terraforming for it), 2x Double Evolution Pill, 3x Fossil Dig, 2x Laggia, and 2x Dolka, a Scrap package of 2x Golem, 1x Chimera, 3x Raptor, 3x Factory, 3x Scrapyard, and 1x Wyvern, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 2x Nibiru, 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, 3x Maxx C, and 2x Veiler, 1x Mare Mare, 1x Destrudo, 2x Avarice, 2x Prosperity(if it was at 3, we would be running 3x), and 2x Called By, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 1x Borreload Savage, 1x Yazi, 1x Formula Synchron, 1x Dugares, 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Accesscode, 1x Knightmare Unicorn, 1x Pentestag, 1x Halqifibrax, and 1x Linkuriboh.

deck_excerpt: Still tweaking this deck, I really like the constant card advantage you can pull with his build.
deck_description: Still tweaking this deck, I really like the constant card advantage you can pull with his build.

Eldlich has been a very viable, and despised, meta-archetype since its release, often a backrow heavy deck that abuses floodgates, however more combo-oriented variants of the deck have been popping up, such as Cyberse, Branded, and Invoked. These decks exchange the excessive use of floodgates and backrow for use of combo starters such as Halqifibrax, Aluber, and Aleister, they are much more fun to play than their base version and make good use of Eldlich's recursive potential for maintain advantage.  For the decklist, we have an Eldlich package of 3x Eldlich, 2x Eldland, 3x Conquistador, 3x Huaquero, and 3x Scarlet Sanguine, a Cyberse package, 3x Gadget, 3x Firewall Guardian, 2x Dotscaper, 1x Accesscode, 1x Transcode, 1x Splash Mage, 1x Devotee, 1x Disciple, 1x Linguriboh, and 1x Linkuriboh, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 2x Nibiru, 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, and 2x Veiler, 1x Scythe, 1x Lancea, 1x Jet Synchron, 1x Change of Heart, 1x One for One, 1x Avarice, 1x Called By, 2x Twin Twisters, 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Trisbaena, 1x Knightmare Unicorn, 2x Dagda, 1x Link Spider, 1x Imduk, and 1x Anima.

deck_excerpt: This is one of the most unknown decks in the NR format
deck_description: Nephthys is a deck that emerged from a proposal that exists in a few archetypes in the game, which is to take a very old card from the game as a base and make an entire deck to support this monster. Here this monster is the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys which is so old that I remember using this card over 12 years ago. Other decks that work with this theme are: Dinosaur structure deck that plays around the Babycerasaurus card and the Thunder Dragon deck that was made to support the iconic early game card. The Nephthys deck works on the basis of Ritual Summon mechanics and has good Ritual monsters which already makes it a decent deck since when it comes to Ritual Summon if the deck cannot generate an advantage while Ritual Summoning it practically becomes unplayable but this is not the case with Nephthys. This archetype preserves some characteristics found on the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys card mainly the fact that they work by destroying your cards to use their effects and also have effects when they are destroyed. The biggest problem with the Nephthys deck is that they copied the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys part of activating their effects on the GY only on their next Standby Phase which makes them slow cards for Yugioh! Modern. However, we are talking about the use of this deck in NR format and here the Nephthys deck is not that slow, even having a competitive attachment. /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Nephthys Gameplay Details: The main idea of ​​the deck is to make the following combo: - Use Manju or Disciple of Nephthys eff to add the missing combo piece to the hand either Devotee of Nephthys which can be added with both cards or Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys which can be added by Manju. - Having the Ritual spell and monster you Ritual Summon Devotee of Nephthys. Then use Devotee eff and special Disciple of Nephthys straight from the deck. (If you already control Disciple and used effect on turn you can bring it to Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys or Matriarch of Nephthys from Deck) - Disciple is the ROTA of both Monster and Spell/Trap. In this case the monster you add is the Matriarch of Nephthys (Follow Up) but it depends on the rest of your hand. - Use Disciple and Devotee to LINK-2 Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver and eff to Add Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys (single target possible) from Deck and Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys from GY. - Using Devotee of Nephthys eff destroys Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys in Hand to Special itself and the Sacred Phoenix already comes into circulation on returning from GY in the Standby Phase of your next turn destroying all the backrow on the field. If you use Devotee of Nephthys itself to Ritual Summon Devotee you get an additional pop from the Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys so always try to capitalize on that play by Ritual Summoning and surprising your opponent by destroying their cards without targeting. One way to take advantage of Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys is with SPELL Last Hope of Nephthys destroying it and an opponent's card. If you have 2 Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys in the GY that were destroyed and you are in your Standby Phase, what happens will be that both of them return to the field with their mandatory effects and activate their mandatory effect to destroy the spells/traps on the field as well. In this NR format build, arriving at the Devotee of Nephthys Ritual Summon is the main move to be made, so even if you don't come with your hand aligned, always seek to access the missing pieces like Devotee and the Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys as soon. Cool that you destroying the Paleozoic Traps in your HAND to use the Disciple of Nephthys effect per example doesn't generate you any downside because they come back from the GY allowing RANK-2 plays. Matriarch of Nephthys allows accessing RANK-2 moves very easily so it is common in the grind game to use Disciple of Nephthys to add Matriarch to be your Normal Summon. And you can use Disciple to destroy the Matriarch if you have it in hand and the Matriarch goes back to the field in the next Standby Phase and gives Disciple Reborn if it's in the GY. The LINK-2 Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver is like a Preparation of Rites in the sense that it can give you a Plus 1 if you have a Ritual Spell in your GY which most of the time you do it you will. And his effect of destroying a "Nephthys" and bringing a different name instead is very useful to Loop the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys during SP to clear Backrow. Torrential Tribute triggers eff from your Nephthys monsters so losing your board is no problem because your cards have floating effects in the Standby Phase. Interaction with Geonator Transverser is also very cool because if you gave SS from Matriarch of Nephthys in the Standby Phase by its own effect and gave Reborn from Devotee of Nephthys from GY and made Geonator Transverser you can use Devotee eff in GY to get back on Geonator's arrow and that way you can exchange the control of monsters. ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////// Disregard the Side Deck, they are just examples of cards to test in the deck.

deck_excerpt: Phantasm Spiral for Master Duel Normal/Rare format
deck_description: Phantasm Spiral is an Anti-Meta style deck that works around Normal Monsters, with the deck's Boss Monster being the Phantasm Spiral Dragon. But the archetype's main card is the excellent Field Spell Pacifis, the Phantasm City that you want access to as soon as possible. In the N/R format version many consistency cards don't exist so we have to adapt the deck with the best in the format like Link Apple which is basically an Upstart Goblin "free to play" and Planet Pathfinder which is 3 more copies from Pacifis, the Phantasm City. (One detail about how Phantasm Spiral cards work is that monsters from the Extra Deck with No effect are not considered Normal monsters like Monk of the Tenyi or Gem-Knight Pearl which is used in the Extra Deck just for decoration because it's correct you never do them as this disables their interaction traps like Phantasm Spiral Battle and Phantasm Spiral Power) /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Comments on cards and deck gameplay: One of the biggest problems with this Archetype is that you have practically no interaction with the opponent until you control a Normal Monster since almost all spell/traps need this condition in order to activate their effects. And there's the fact that if your opponent is smart he can easily play around Pacifis, the Phantasm City by not activating any card effects but trying to win on the basis of Beatdown by putting monsters on the field and going straight to the Battle Phase. That's why I decided to give up using Megalosmasher X which has the synergy of being a WATER monster with the Trap Sea Stealth Attack that can banish it to protect Pacifis, the Phantasm City from being destroyed to use the Mekk-Knight engine: World Legacy's Memory and Mekk-Knight Avram, these two cards play the role of Unexpected Dai better since you can use it on your opponent's turn and the monster Special Summoned by World Legacy's Memory will be returned to the hand in the End Phase which means you can Normal Summon Mekk-Knight Avram on your next turn and trigger the effect of Pacifis, the Phantasm City to add another Archetype card and build pressure on the opponent faster than compared to Unexpected Dai and Megalosmasher X . The only thing about using World Legacy's Memory is that it conflicts with Pacifis, the Phantasm City effect of creating Token so it has to be used after creating the Token to Summon Mekk-Knight Avram. Other synergies of this engine: World Legacy's Memory makes Planet Pathfinder even better in the deck because before you had to choose between Normal Summoning Megalosmasher X or Pathfinder but now you have the option to bring Vanilla straight from the deck. And about Mekk-Knight Avram coming back into the hand in the End Phase you get a simple discard way to use Paleozoic Dinomischus. So the improvements in using this engine are better than any other option available in Normal/Rare format. Basically Phantasm Spiral Battle allows you to catch the opponent off guard when for example you used the effect of one of the Equip and it is now equipped on the Boss Monster of the deck and now it's the opponent's turn and he declares an attack on your monster that doesn't have the equip spell, you can activate Trap Phantasm Spiral Battle in the attack declaration and return the Equip Spell to your monster that is participating in the battle and take advantage of that battle phase in the opponent's turn. The best Equip spell is Phantasm Spiral WAVE because your monster doesn't need to have battled an opponent's monster to resolve and bring the boss monster, as well as forcing the opponent to discard a card from their hand. Sea Stealth Attack is the best way to get rid of the token on the field so you can use the field's effect again to generate advantage and interaction every turn. Mainly do this on your turn to enter the Opponent's Turn without Token if Already have another Normal Monster on the Field. Another Missplay with Sea Stealth Attack is not banishing NORMAL Monsters knowing that you will need to use TORRENTIAL TRIBUTE. (Know that using Sea Stealth Attack eff on Megalosmasher X per example will count as a monster that returns to the field in the End Phase and not a Special Summon so you will never get trigger eff from FIELD Pacifis, the Phantasm City with this effect) The Field spell Pacifis, the Phantasm City basically works like this: The Phantasm Spiral Token create effect is not once per turn and the add effect from deck to hand is MANDATORY. The Tenyi Counter Trap Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi only negates spell/trap activation and not their effect on the GY like Eldlich's traps like Conquistador of the Golden Land and True Draco cards like True Draco Heritage. Don't forget how important Paleozoic Traps are in the deck coming back from the GY as a Normal Monster having a lot of synergy with deck cards that get dead while a normal monster is not on the field. Interaction between Sea Stealth and Paleozoic Traps: you can activate Sea Stealth Attack and in chain activate the Paleozoic Traps in GY to gain access to a Normal Monster. //////////////////////////////////////////////// ////////////Deck issues: Lack of pressure and consistency due to reliance on Field Spell Pacifis, the Phantasm City alongside cards like Sea Stealth Attack to capitalize on advantage. So in addition to having a certain dependence on the opponent's actions, what you do is never enough to control the game, you are always losing until the moment when the opponent's pushes miraculously end and you win. That's why this is a deck that won't tolerate Missplay on your part. //////////////////////////////////////////////// //////////// Disregard the Side Deck, they are just card options to test in the Main Deck.

deck_excerpt: Updated version of Battlewasp Ballpark deck for Master Duel NR format.
deck_description: I have already participated in two Master Duel tournaments focused on the Normal/Rare Format. And I got addicted to building several decks of this format because it's an event still little explored and full of good archetype ideas to use. The deck I present below is the improved version of the first Master Duel Normal/Rare deck I built: https://ygoprodeck.com/battlewasp-ballpark-nr-event-mar22/ Lately I stopped playing Master Duel because I have an error problem that prevents me from playing any game because a window appears that closes the game. I've already talked to the game's support and they gave me a lot of attention but the fact is that even with a print screen and details of how the error happens, I haven't been able to play for almost a month. So I decided to make some deck profiles of decks I had built in Normal/Rare Format and share my latest content related to Master Duel. //////////////////////////////////////////////// /// As I had already explained in the other deck profile the idea behind the deck and the synergies between the main cards used, here I will focus on the interactions I noticed when using the deck in tournaments that allowed me to improve it a lot. Shinobi and Gokipole Interaction: You make the Shinobi Insect Hagakuremino using the Gokipole as a material and pointing at an opponent's monster and the Gokipole uses its Special Summon effect from Vanilla Shiny Black "C" Squadder in the zone the Shinobi points to and destroys the opponent's monster that Shinobi points to which triggers the Shinobi's eff to give Reborn from Sting the Poison for example and you do Synchro-6 Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge to end the game. In other situations you can Reborn a Level 3 Insect to make XYZ Summon rolls. I've won several games just because of this interaction. Just remember that when making Shinobi using Gokipole and Battlewasp - Twinbow the Attacker you don't first bring Gokipole with Shinobi after the opponent's monster is destroyed, but Twinbow because he will be banished when he leaves the field and will not use its search effect. This same interaction is valid for Puzzlomino and Gokipole: You make Puzzlomino, the Drop-n-Deleter using Gokipole as material and bring Vanilla Shiny Black "C" Squadder in the zone he points and destroy an opponent's monster and you will still be able to manipulate its level to destroy another opponent's monster or make XYZ Summon or Synchro Summon plays. So Puzzlomino is another interaction and versatility card available in the Extra Deck when you are not locked in Insects. //////////////////////////////////////////////// /// Technoplay and Missplays I made with the deck: You should think a lot about the best time to use Reborn spell Revival Swarm eff in GY to protect one of your Insect monsters from destruction. For example I already lost a game because I decided not to protect Synchro-6 Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge with it since I had Torrential Tribute set to use on the opponent's turn. Another mistake I made a few times was when using the Giant Ballpark effect to send to the GY because the decision to special summon 1, 2 or 3 copies of Shiny Black "C" Squadder is important for example if you drop 1 Vanilla in the Main Deck on your next turn you will be able to use this special summon effect again, which in this case would be the 3 Vanillas. So don't bring the 3 Shiny Black "C" Squadder Vanillas straight onto the field the first time you activate the Giant Ballpark effect. There's also the interaction between Special Summoning 2 Lv4 Vanilla and you do RANK-4 Insect Number 70: Malevolent Sin and then RANK-5 Digital Bug Corebage on top to have interaction of returning a defense position monster to the deck . Another missplay that you shouldn't commit when using Giant Ballpark is that its floating effect of giving Vanilla Reborn is only when an Insect is destroyed by an opponent's card effect. So first that if you destroy your monsters with Torrential Tribute, Ballpark won't trigger eff from Reborn to Vanilla, and second that it won't trigger eff if the monsters are destroyed in battle so think carefully about using this card so you don't missplay in battle phase for example thinking she would give Vanilla Reborn. MISSPLAY: You have a lot of cards that need to discard as cost to work so don't keep setting cards on the field for no reason as when you need a discard in your hand to resolve a Dinomischus or Lightning Vortex this mistake will cost you the game. MISSPLAY: You don't summon Synchro 6 Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge in the Extra Monster Zone Column to make the Shinobi Co-Linked so the opponent can target him for attacks. //////////////////////////////////////////////// /// In a format like this N/R with slower games and Spell/Traps based interactions you should save your Backrow removal as a Mystical Space Typhoon to use on the right cards. It's not to use Mystical Space Typhoon blindly, for example, but to wait for the game to develop a little to destroy the correct backrow. //////////////////////////////////////////////// // Disregard the Side Deck, they are just examples of interesting cards to test in the deck.

deck_excerpt: A Fun and Competitive Deck for the Common Charity Format
deck_description: Here is the Deck I've been testing for Konami's Common Charity format. It's a hybrid Tenyi build that focuses on some elements of control but also works to swarm the field with monsters while maintaining a decent hand advantage. To begin, our Tenyi core consists of three Ashuna, three Vishuda, two Nahata, two Mapura, two Shthana, and two Adhara. For those of you who don't know, the Main-Deck Tenyi monsters all have the effect to special summon from hand while you control no monsters, or all the monsters on your side of the field are Non-Effect. They work to swarm onto the field so you can link climb into their boss monster, Berserker of the Tenyi. If you control at least one Non-Effect monster the Tenyi's will also have a secondary effect. By banishing themselves from hand or grave: Ashuna can summon another Tenyi from the deck, Vishuda can target a card your opponent controls and return it to the hand, Nahata can reduce an opponent's monsters attack by 1500, Mapura can negate a card that target's one of your Non-Effect monsters, Shthana can reborn one of your Non-Effect monsters that was destroyed by battle or card effect then if successful, destroy one monster your opponent controls, and Adhara can recycle one of your banished Tenyi monsters back to your hand. This core allows us to maintain a powerful board presence with a few negates and have some play on the crack back if our board does get broken. For the rest of the Monsters, we play two Lava Golem and a Pankratops to stop our opponent from gaining a strong a field presence. Two Mimicking Man-Eater Bug that when face down, still allows you to summon Tenyi monsters, and when flipped face-up will have the effect to target a monster your opponent controls, destroy it, and then gain that monster's original attack and type. Man-Eater also has the bonus of not being able to be destroyed by monsters with the type you just acquired. In addition, we also run two Battle Faders to prevent the opponent from attacking directly. Finally, to round out the monsters, we have two Droll and one Veiler as the hand traps. For the spells, we have: one Change of Heart to take control of an opponents monster, two Raigeki to clear the board, two Vessel for the Dragon Cycle to add a Wyrm to hand and fill the grave with a Tenyi, a Terraforming for the field spell, a Foolish Burial to fill your grave with a Tenyi, not in hand, a Monster Reborn to recycle a monster and gain an advantage, and finally one Flawless Protection of the Tenyi to protect our Non-Effect monsters and once per turn draw two if your opponents has special summoned an effect monster. For the Traps, we are running: two Swordsoul Blackout to destroy two cards on our opponent's field, three Threatening Roar to skip our opponent's battle phase, and two Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi. This card is an Omni-negate that can trigger as long as you control a Non-Effect monster and if destroyed by your opponent card effect allows you to summon a Non-Effect monster from the Extra Deck negating its summoning conditions. In the Extra Deck, we have three Monk of the Tenyi and one Lanphorhynchus, easy link climbing fodder for your main deck Tenyi's. One Geonator Transverser to trade monsters. Two Shaman of the Tenyi to bring back a Wyrm from the grave. One Ra'Ten and one Sahasrara to help flood the field. Two Berserker of the Tenyi to act as a Non-Effect beat stick. One Yazi and One Catastor for the synchros, one Tornado Dragon for spell and trap removal, and one Master of Oz which is a High attack normal monster that can be bolstered by the Tenyi's effects. The side is pretty self-explanatory, Ash Blosssom, Ghost Ogre, and Veiler are all great hand traps. Artifact Scythe can be used with Tornado Dragon to lock your opponent out of the extra deck, Vanity's Fiend can be summoned with one Tenyi and locks special summoning, two Dragon Cycle for searching and summoning, and an extra Flawless Perfection if you really need to draw it, There's no perfect end board for this deck it's built to adapt and change with games and prevent your opponent from gaining an advantage. For the most part, you want to focus on link climbing and special summoning with your main deck Tenyi's, setting up a board that has a few Non-Effect monsters like Monk or Berserker on board and a few Tenyi's in the grave. You'll also want to rely on the disruption this deck provides by using the traps, Man-Eater Bugs, and Droll's to stop your opponent from comboing off. Some of the funny techs this deck is able to provide is to use Blackout on your Non-Effect monster, pop two cards your opponent control, use Shthana to bring back your Non-Effect, and pop a monster on your opponent's side, essentially taking three off your opponent's field. You can set Mimicking Man-Eater Bug on your field, Summon Lava Golem to your opponents, pass turn your opponent takes 1000, then if attacked Man-Eater Bug can flip face-up, gain the attack of the Lava Golem and destroy it clearing your opponents 3000 monster. Utilizing the side deck you can set Scythe, special summoning one level four Tenyi and normal summon another level four, overlay for Tornado Dragon, then on your opponent's turn use the effect to detach one, pop the Scythe, and lock your opponent out of their extra deck for the turn. If your opponent is playing a deck with heavy back-row removal you can set Fists, bait out a destruction effect, then when destroyed special summon Master of Oz which, as a Normal beat-stick, is still protected by Tenyi effects. Anyway thanks for reading. -HeyJoshRob
Morphtronic Gadget (May 2022)

deck_excerpt: Combined idea of the floating Myutant boss monsters effects w/ the floating Despia/Branded/Albaz fusion monster effects :)
deck_description:
To start off, I'm not good at deck building 2 archetypes like this nor am I really knowledgeable about the Branded/Despia/Albaz style so if there's any help/suggestions I'd really appreciate it! This idea kind of popped into my head when playing pure Myutants and realized "Despia Theater is for a generic fusion summoning isn't it?"

  • Strategy
    • Myutants: For the most part the Myutants are kind of just there for big bodies and disruptions. If I don't want to go into the big fusions immediately I rely of the despia aspect. The archetype has some nice floating effects (Beast -> Traps, Mist -> Monsters & Arsenal -> Spells). I would have ran 3 of all the level & lower Myutants but it felt too much. "Myutant Mutant" & Lab are both great extenders and Lab is a nice reload in case I draw one of the boss monsters. They're just so dang fun, we need more support!
    •  Despia: Like I said, no clue how to build with Albaz lol I was considering using Dogmatika for this but since it's mostly a fusion heavy deck I didn't want to be locked out of the extra deck. The other part of the strategy is to utilize Tragedy and Opening for the main combo (Opening -> send Tragedy -> SS Aluber -> chain both effects -> profit) I also wasn't quite sure what the extra deck should look like so I just set up the extra deck with 2 of most of the fusions and do all the fusion shenanigans. Incredible Ecclesia is solid enough as a 1 of, especially since it's ~$80 GEEZ!
    • Overall: The deck is very weak to negations and handtraps, the Myutants can play around Ash pretty well but things like Effect Veiler, Droll, and others can hit this deck hard. It also has a hard time with backrow removal so it makes it a little hard in that regard too. My side deck is for those occasions when the hand traps are too much of a problem and for some different tech options. Like Tragedy discarded for Twin Twisters and Traptrick to get a Myutant Cry faster.
    • Notes: If you banish Tragedy for the cost of the Myutants it won't work :/ Had to learn that the hard way when I got judge ruled 3 times lol. I did consider running E. Teleport but Im just not sure what to take out ya know? Lastly Thank you again for reading and i look forward to reading any advise! :)

deck_excerpt: "Cyber Dragon" "Therion" "Invoked".  Not gonna lie, this deck is actually much better than I thought it would be. If you want to put 2 Mechaba and a
deck_description: I like Mechaba so much, I decided "Why not put up a Mechaba with a Mechaba?" The idea is pretty simple - Between Aleister and the Hex-Seals there are a lot of copies of "Aleister" to fuse with. Power Bond can serve as a back-up for Invocation to make Mechaba, usually making Mechaba #1. Herz is the ideal companion here - Herz can add a Cyber Dragon to your hand from your deck when it goes to the GY to set up Fusion plays, but it gets better from there. Pitch it with Mechaba, and you can use its effect to pick itself back up, meaning one copy fuels a single Mechaba for multiple turns. Additionally, if Therion "King" Regulus is equipped with Herz, when Regulus sends itself to the GY you can search (or pick back up) a Cyber Dragon. So this deck always has fuel for Mechaba. That's literally the deck, set up 3 Negates, then later kill with Chimeratechs, or use Chimeratechs to break boards and then set up negates if you can't OTK. You probably can. I believe in you! Or just attack with Cyber Dragon!

deck_excerpt: Do you think Konami stays silent about its card design philosophy because it too lives in fear of what it's created?
deck_description: There are so many fusion engines in this game, man. So, naturally, there comes a time when you look at a pile of purple cards and ask yourself: "how many of these can I cram into a deck and still be playable?" and turns out the answer is: "around five or six".  Your best cards are Branded Fusion and Rainoheart since are one card starters. Thankfully, both are accessible by Emergency Teleport-like effects (Branded Opening and Fusion Deployment). This frees the space for your normal summon so I decided to play the second best fusion normal summon (don't worry, He will make a cameo on this list anyway) without a tutor from deck spell card: Dinomorphia Therizia which searches the frankly absurd Dinomorphia Frenzy to go into Rexterm for a big floodgate. The funny thing is... There's still space for another floodgate in the form of Shaddoll Winda. SInce Branded Fusion is one of the most busted cards in recent memory, you can easily make her by sending Squamata or Beast when fusing Lubellion. If two floodgates aren't enough for you, oh boy, I have great news! By just adding one brick in the form of the dark Hex Sealed monster, you can also make Invoked Caliga if you dump it with Branded Fusion (which at this point is the atlas that carries half the format -which it says a lot considering it's also a format with full power Adventurer engine-). Honestly, at this point I was losing my mind by seriously considering playing Fusion Destiny since it's not only searchable by Alba-Lenatus, but you can also play Destiny Hero Malicious instead of Dasher to have an extra body on the field which can also be recycled by your Tearalaments and play it as if it wasn't semi-limited. Sadly I didn't do it in the end since the way this version of the deck works, you get locked into fusions most of the time so you couldn't really take advantage of this interaction. That being said, I hope someone finds a way to take full advantage of it.  DISCLAIMER: You should really be looking for a Tearalaments/Branded list, since it's the real best version of the deck.
This is a D/D/D deck.  If you have any advice on how to improve this deck, feel free to leave a comment!

deck_excerpt: This is a decklist I made from only 3x Structure Deck Albaz Strike
deck_description:
This is a decklist I made from only 3x Structure Deck Albaz Strike I play back to the front at 3 to scythe lock the opponent, essentially:
  • open back to the front
  • resolve branded fusion, summoning Albion the Branded Dragon, send scythe from deck as material
  • on your opponents standby, flip back to the front summon scythe

My latest take on Scrap Machina Trains, now with the big new hit, Regulus!  The idea behind the deck, initially, was to take advantage of the various interactions between Urgent Schedule, Machina Citadel, and Scrap Recycler (with the Wyvern). Looking at Regulus, I immediately liked it in the deck. Often this deck put up a Super Dora + Apollousa going first, but I love the idea of adding an easy maindeck omni, especially since Citadel + Regulus is a low-end board I can get behind.  So, it's an Urgent Schedule deck. The idea behind this card is simple - if you're going second, this card is going to make you Scrap Wyvern to pop cards, it is going to give you material for Unicorn, Accesscode (and Phoenix) to break board, and when you pop the Scrap Recycler with the Wyvern, it'll revive big daddy Citadel to add a 10 to your board, or just put up a board wipe. However, if you're going first, this card can add a level 10 Machine to your hand if you pop it with Wyvern, so this will help extend your combos. Also, this card can be a mini "scapegoat" that can save your bacon in a situation where you set it. 3 of it and the Recycler are mandatory. I'm on Raptor as my Wyvern brick, because it will get the second Recycler trigger going, but is also a back-up starter, albeit a much worse one.  I'm a big fan of the Irradiator/Megaform/Redeployment trick, so I'm running it here. Redeployment is an insane card, and helping set up my GY while guaranteeing a Citadel is super sweet.  I'm on all 7 legal copies of Regulus. There are a few reasons for this - firstly, redundant copies are good food for Fortress, but also work just with themselves to get you extra negation, and can even be played in multiple ways, so I'm cool on running multiple Regulus. Also the field spell is nuts. Additionally, the Field spell can be popped by Wyvern, so it does double duty. But the main reason is that I think this deck barely has legs without Regulus, and I wanted to really maximize my chances of seeing Regulus. This card is sort of like a Gryphon Rider for the deck defensively, and is busted in multiples, so I really wanted to max out and run all 7.  This deck is hurt by the Auroradon hit, but because your bread-and-butter was Wyvern, not Halq, it isn't a big deal. It does mean the end of the easy 3 Omni + Citadel setups, but Apollo + Citadel + Regulus should be fine (and occasionally you might sneak in a Super Dora, if you're feeling frisky, over the Citadel). Also, remember that Urgent Schedule prevents you from attacking with non Machine monsters - Regulus and Citadel are still live, and "Choo choo!" hitting them with a train is still on the table, but Accesscode is just to shred their board - otherwise build Apollo.

deck_description: Tearalaments is a new archetype in Yu-Gi-Oh based around fusion monsters, however they do not have an in-archetype fusion spell. Instead, the Main Deck monsters can activate an effect that can fuse monsters together by shuffling them from the hand, field or GY back into the deck, making them very recursive. Shove the best deck right now into the archetype and you have a pretty solid meta list centered around fusion summoning.  For the decklist, we have a Tearalaments package of 2x Shaylen, 3x Reinoheart, 2x Haufenis, 2x Meirrow, 3x Ruined Realm(and 1x Terraforming and 1x Metaverse for it), 3x Crime, 3x Kaleido-Heart, and 2x Kitkalos, we have a Branded package of 1x Dramaturge, 1x Ad Libitum, 2x Albion the Shrouded, 3x Aluber, 2x Albaz, 2x Tragedy, 3x Lost, 3x Fusion, 3x Red, 3x Opening, 1x Chimera, 1x Mirrorjade, 3x Lubellion, 1x Quaeritis, 2x Albion the Branded, and 1x Masquerade, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have  my preferred lineup of Handtraps, 2x Nibiru, 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, 3x Maxx C, and 2x Veiler, 3x Galaxy Cyclone, 3x Grass, 2x Called By, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 1x Underworld Goddess.

deck_excerpt: The Meta defier and the Meta denier merge into one entity sworn to deny each other's presence....
deck_description: Video is linked down below - Exo ( https://youtube.com/watch?v=rQOcy4wDxH8&t ) Once again, Eldlich the Golden Lord is off creating the usual confusion a havoc he does best. However the twist this time might be the most delirious attempt to make, to make any bizarre Eldlich variant into a niche experience. By incorporating the golden lord with the protectors of Necrovalley, you become God of the GY and not just your GY. All of this while building the boards you usually do with the both of them separately, and returning the favor of giving your opponent temporary floodgates.   So where to begin? Well there is the usual Eldlich package, which contains cards such as Cursed Eldland and Eldlixir of Scarlett Sanguine to either recover the Golden Lord from the GY or add him to the hand from the Deck. Next comes his minions; however the only two "playable" pieces in his arsenal are Conquistador of the Golden Land and Huaquero of the Golden Land. Simply put it that while there it isn't too much for him to offer when played alone; the way I assumed (from the last two years of seeing him being played) he was always meant to be played was as a hybrid piece that at least tries to have synergy with Eldlich. That being said the Gravekeeper archetype (a counter to Eldlich) coincidentally works well with Eldlich, regardless of Necrovalley's GY negation somewhat being a problem for the deck.   Now the answers on how in the world does Eldlich the Golden Lord get the pass the one field spell that stops it from doing what it does pass. For starters there is one monster in the Gravekeeper parable know to treat itself as the same infamous while on the field while on the field; but the catch is that it doesn't give off the GY negation effect the original field spell does (known truly as Gravekeeper's Priestess). As a result of having both Gravekeeper's Priestess and Necrovalley in my deck, I can do the usual combo setup I can attend to do, and then once done (if I can) go into Necrovalley pass for my opponents turn. This is useful because with the returning prevalence of GY effects (and the fact that the Branded Dragons use monsters in the GY as extensions for fusion summons), this puts a halt on any advance if they rely on their GY for any plays whatsoever. Then if you want to get rid of the said Necrovalley that is on the field at the beginning of your turn (regardless if you have a priestess or not), just scoop it with your Eldlich the Golden Lord.   As for your Extra deck, it is important to note that not all of them are gonna be used to the fullest extent, and sometimes would be fodder for Pot of Prosperity. However in this case, just about all the cards in the Extra deck did not go untouched through out all my matches. This is because I tried to make sure to find the ones best suited for situations where I could make use of them to the best I can. The card Traptrix Rafflesia is a new addition in any of my decks, as it can detach one material to copy one "Trap-Hole" trap card milled to the GY by it's effect. Next comes the centerpiece of the Gravekeeper archetype, Gravekeeper's Supernaturalist (a card that can't be destroyed by card effects if Necrovalley is on the field; but can search a Gravekeeper or Necrovalley card at the end of your turn). Then comes the additions of both Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustorous and Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy; and if you played in the format long enough (or played Yu-Gi-Oh the past couple years), you would know what both of them would do and while I added in the deck for a different reasons that each other, both have significant impacts that worked out to getting into either Selene, Queen of Master Magicians or into Accesscode Talker without hesitation.

deck_excerpt: Get overwhelming advantage with Precious Cards from Beyond and slay with Slifer the Sky Dragon all the while controlling the game.
deck_description: The deck is built around Precious Cards from Beyond, which allows you to gain massive advantage everytime you use two tributes for a tribute summon. This, in a Monarch engine, allows you to continuously make plays and gain more options as to what you wish to play - with cards such as Monarchs Stormforth or Ehther the Heavenly Monarch making full use of tributing. This, in tangent with Slifer and Soul Crossing, incites major card advantage while getting rid of opponent's monsters. Slifer also acts as a disruption against some decks and incompotent foes who can't read, as no one ever seems to realise Slifer has a really powerful last effect - reducing any opponent's monster summoned in ATK position's attack by 2000 and destroying it if it becomes 0 ATK because of this. But no matter how I put it, its still a glorified control deck that tries to limit opponent's plays and summons. Still extremely fun tributing your opponent's monsters to summon Slifer and beat them up with it. For just a look at what to do when you stare at me ranting on, just look at the boldened text to learn of the main premise. Squad Goals: Your main goal in the beginning is to get out or search for our starter, Edea the Heavenly Squire, who will then be summoned (preferably SS'd so you can tribute summon twice) and activate its effect to summon Eidos the Underworld Squire. Eidos allows for another tribute summon upon him entering the field this turn. Before tributing these two into a Monarch from hand, you should first try and get Pantheism of the Monarchs in the banished zone by using its effect to search for either disruption or continuation. Alternatively, if Pantheism has already been used or is not accessible, The Prime Monarch is a preferable substitute as it can banish a useful card in your GY. After a Monarchs spell/trap is in the banished zone that you want, you can use: The Monarchs Stormforth (if an opponent has a monster), Return of the Monarchs or Precious Cards from Beyond to gain advantage. Preferably, use as many as possible but be cautious in decking out with Precious Cards from Beyond. Tributing into a Monarch now allows you to use their effect which can be chained with Edea in order to stop it from being negated. Caius is an extremely powerful asset against most decks as targetting and banishing a Dark Monster on the field makes your opponent have to banish every single copy of it no matter where it is, effectively shutting down a lot of decks that are reliant on said monster - an example is Eldlich, go make them cry. You do not specifically have to target a Dark Monster, you can target any card, but it is advised to do so if they don't benefit from it. He (she?) can also instead banish TWO cards if you tributed a dark monster (Eidos) so it can have the option of shutting down more of the opponent's plays. Furthermore, the card even does 1000 LP burn when you target and successfully banish - adding that small bit of burn that can end up winning games. Ehther can be a massive impact as it gets another beatstick out on the field (preferably a second Ehther) which is returned to the hand during the EP, this effect is even better due to it sending two monarch cards - either thinning the deck out of now useless cards or setting up for a Pantheism banish effect / Prime Monarch summon. Ehther is also interaction as, by banishing a Monarch spell/trap in GY, you can tribute summon it on your opponent's turn - combo this with The Monarchs Stormforth to be able to tribute an opponent's monster for free and possibly interrupt them. Erebus is a powerful threat under certain circumstances due to its effect of shuffling an opponent's card (from field, graveyard or randomly from hand) with the same "send two" as Ehther, but the card really shines in the graveyard in which it allows for recycling at the cost of a Monarch spell/trap in hand which can further create more plays. Erebus is also needed for Return of the Monarchs, in which you can either search for it or search with it depending on which you summoned. If there is no advantage in using more than one tribute, you can set up Domain before the tribute summon to reduce the level of the Monarch in hand to LVL 6, meaning it only requires one tribute to be summoned. You can also tribute summon a Monarch using just one tribute summoned monster if neccessary - but it is unrecommended to do so as you're wasting potential growth in your board. Eidos' GY effect can also be activated to SS Edea from the graveyard. If you know you have an extra Edea you can summon and make plays with, then you can not bother with saving it and can just use it straight up for a tribute material for even more advantage - but otherwise it would be advised to save it for your next turn so Edea's summoning effect can be used. Finally, you can just set your traps or quick-plays to have interaction. Soul Crossing is one example as you can tribute three of your opponent's monsters to get out Slifer, which both the tribute and Slifer itself can greatly hinder their turn. Also, highly suggested you play Domain somewhere in your turn so that the opponent has to slay the tribute summoned cards before being able to access the Extra Deck. Caution: Using Soul Crossing limits you to only one more activation that is not Slifer's effects or any Divine-Beasts so try and use it towards the end of your turn to just not care about this limitation. Monarchs Stormforth and, I believe, Soul Crossing don't allow for the tributing of non-affected monsters as the spell itself would be affecting it. This means that you can still tribute a monster that is unaffected by everything but spells, yet some cards are thus difficult to get over without Slifer beatstick. Anchamoufrite is a free draw when put in the pendulumn scale and can be SS'd from the extra for the harsh price of nothing. Caius is not optional, so if you tribute summon it and the opponent has no cards to target then say your goodbyes to one of your own cards. Don't deck out with Precious Cards from Beyond, its effect isn't optional BUT using Soul Crossing means that only one can activate - use that and the fact you can use the Monarch's effect (to only need to tribute one tribute summoned monster) or Domain to lower its LVL to 6 so as to not fulfill the "two tributes" part as you will. Don't die of laughter when you kill yourself with Precious Cards from Beyond or when you direct attack with Slifer for 12000 LP, haha. Most importantly, good luck and draw the out.

deck_excerpt: A very nice and versatile Antimeta Stun deck to play in Edison (March 2010 banlist) format!
deck_description:
Here we are, an Edison version of one of my favourite decks (of which I have uploaded multiple versions), taking inspiration from the decklist I used to run in 2012. I also took a little inspiration from a very nice deck I've found on the official Edison Format website. As a gentle reminder, you can use this website to check the card pool of the Edison format and this website to check the Edison forbidden & limited cards list. The deck could easily work well with 40 to 42 cards, but no more than that.

Strategy:

Basically, we want to stun the opponent blocking every dangerous move with lots of traps and monsters which avoid special summoning, banish cards, bounce monsters, etc etc. A concrete risk is to run out of cards, so the Morphing Jar is usually a very pleasant hand reload The Extra Deck is not used except for the Stardust Dragon, it's there just for a reference of good generic Synchros for this format. The Side Deck probably has room for improvements, the most important card is King Tiger Wanghu that could turn out to be incredibly useful.

Variations:

More: - Gorz the Emissary of Darkness (just add one, can save from some last second disaster) - Dimensional Fissure (we could run x1/2 more in the Main Deck or in the Side Deck, for the moment I feel like we have enough removals or maybe it's too much already) - Book of Moon (super strong card, it's not limited in this format so I'm tempted to run more of those) - Smashing Ground (super strong card, it's not limited in this format so I'm tempted to run more of those) - Starlight Road (could be better to use directly 2 in the Main Deck, but depends on how frequently it's possible to encounter mass removals) - Legendary Jujitsu Master (is a very powerful card, maybe run it in Main Deck instead of the Beast King Barbaros or simply as an addition) Less: - Dimensional Fissure (I have lots of doubts about this card, it's very strong, but I don't know if increase it or move it to the Side Deck, maybe it's redundant) - Dark Bribe (Having x2 in Main Deck and x1 in Side Deck could be too much, might consider removing x1 copy from one of the two decks) - Royal Oppression (Depends on the opponents, but could be useful to move x1 copy from Main Deck to Side Deck)

Useful cards:

- Black Horn of Heaven - Banisher of the Light - Raigeki Break - Torrential Tribute - D.D. Assailant - D.D. Crow - Kycoo the Ghost Destroyer - Gold Sarcophagus - Trap Dustshot - Skill Drain - Call of the Haunted Can't wait to complete this deck and play some old-style games! I invite you to take a look at my other decks, and leave some comments and likes!

deck_excerpt: An Antimeta Stun deck which gave its best at the end of my best period from 2009 to 2012, giving me a lot of joy and wins!
deck_description: I was lucky enough, as a kid, to play the game during its very best phase, from 2009 until 2012. This is my old Antimeta from 2012 (respects the March 2012 banlist) which was always in my backpack at the time. A similar version could be nowadays played in Edison Format (March 2010 banlist) with few modifications. In fact, I continued updating my deck until I kept playing the game regularly, which means somewhere in Summer 2012 (i.e. a couple of banlists ahead of Edison). I'd like to create an Edison version of this deck in the future. The core idea of the deck is to summon some good troublemakers as Fossil Dyna Pachycephalo and/or Thunder King Rai-Oh whose effects will start blocking the opponent's moves. You want to do everything you can to defend the one which stops your opponent as much as possible and you have plenty of choices to do so. The Doomcaliber Knight is quite predictable, but a nice attacking monster which also creates some troubles. Also, the Neo-Spacian Grand Mole is useful to push back the Synchros from where they come from. The Effect Veiler is for emergencies and the Banisher of the Radiance and the King Tiger Wanghu are good if the opponent uses the graveyard (which is quite common) or small monsters respectively. Cards will go away very quickly from your hand and field since you will activate lots of traps and spells, that's why we have the Morphing Jar for a quick reload (might as well disrupt the opponent's plans) and the Pot of Duality doen no interfere with our plans since we do not special summon a lot. The extra deck is not relevant to our purposes except for what we could summon in the very rare occasion we use the Veiler as a tuner or when we activate the Starlight Road. In the side deck we can keep cards based on the meta, but I wasn't using it very much at the time. It's such a throwback to write this in 2022 and I sincerely hope to bring back some sweet memories to you as well, I'd love to see your old decks from that era and I invite you to like and comment on all my decks if you wish!

Last but not least, I also made a 2022 version of the deck to play the modern game (probably not my cup of tea, but it was fun to think about it and I will test it asap). deck_name: Branded Despia: Different Ratios That You Can Play With
deck_excerpt: Branded Despia with different cards and ratios
deck_description: Instead of playing the usual build, I wanted to challenge myself to make a deck that was still competitive but that just has different cards and ratios.  This is what I made:

First things first this is not the best version of this deck, there are some cards that dont need to be added and others that can be replaced. but this is my little spin on it.

This deck list is mainly a control deck as their is little you can do with combos. This deck is meant to take full advantage of myutants banishing mechanic, by permently whittling down your opponets cars through "Dimension Shifter", "Myutant Mist", "Myutant Arsenal" and "Necroface". While controling your opponents moves with cards like "Summon Limit" and "Myutant Clash". Then "Soul Absorbtion" is a nice little tech that will allow you to gain life with each banished card which pretty much ammounts to every card you use, allowing you to have sustainabilty if they were to ever get through your board.

A good start is if you open with "Myutant M-05/Mytant ST-46" and "Necroface". if you open with "Myutant M-05" you summon it search for "Myutant ST-46" then use "Myutant M-05" Secound effect to banish "Necroface" immediatly milling 5 cards from both of your decks and Summoning Myutant Beast from deck. If you open with "Myutant ST-46" Then you want to summon it instead search for "Myutant EVO Lab", then use "Myutant ST-46" Secound effect to banish "Necroface" summoning "Myutnat  Beast". if you are lucky on the Mill and banish "Myutant M-05" you can then use "Myutant EVO Lab" to special summon it from the Banish zone. which you would use to then search "Myutant ST-46"  and then use it secound effect to banish a trap to summon "Myutant Arsenal" from deck if able to.

A note to add is that the "Necroface"  proc will allow you to see what cards your opponent has in their deck giving you an hint to what they are playing and allowing you to make a more effective strategy.


Knowing that their are better options to play here is a guide if you want to make the deck a bit better.

So just in case i will give you a bit of a better deck list. for monster cards "Myutant Gb-88" and "Myutant Mist" are effects are very specific and when used can easily turn the game arround but just as easily can become brick in your deck. For these cards you can just replace them with any hand trap "Ash, Psyframe Gamma, Max C and Nibiru" would be the most effective. You could also add more Nemese cards for how they take advantage of myutants banishing mechanic and would allow you to add link plays to the deck.

For Spell "Soul Absorbtion" and "Psychic path" are not needed and can be taken out entierly, but their main purpose in the deck is to take advantage of the bainishing mechanic. due to myutants always banishing both you and you're cards, "Soul Absorbtion" will allow for easy life and can keep you in the game for a bit longer. "Psychic path" will allow you to add 2 of you're myutant starters back to hand from the banished zone which can be incredibly powerfull. but overall both of these cards can end up bricking you if drawn at the wrong time.

"Pot of Desires" and "Pot of Extravagence" can easily be switched between each other with absolutly no issue. Both of these cards can be gimmicked with "Necroface", If you are in an advantagous position you can use "Necroface" to shuffle back every banished cards but at the cost of your normal summon. This works better with "Pot of Desires" as the only down side that comes from it is the bannished. "Pot of Extravagence" on the other hand will stop you from using "Myutant Evo Labs" secound effect of allowing you to place one myutant card on the bottom of your deck and draw 1 but that is easily a price worth sacerficing.

Traps you have "Myutant clash". This card will allow you to target negate one monster card on the field but it require you to have a myutant monster in the graveyard to do this. its secound effect being allowing you to draw one for when a level-8 myutant destroys a monster by battle. This effect can be good but overall it can be replaced with Imperm which has overall just has better effect. You can also switch this out for "There Can Only Be One" as Myutants are able to take advantage of this card to full effect.

deck_name: Solfachord Master Duel for Pendulum Beginners
deck_excerpt: Solfachord guide for beginners to pendulum summoning.  Assumes you have completed the pendulum tutorial in solo mode.
deck_description:
Solfachord is a fun pendulum deck quite difficult to master and expensive to make, but rewarding in its own right. While I consider this the most consistent version, please consider using the suggested alternatives in the side deck if you already have them.

Inherent Weakness of Pendulum Summoning : Pendulums require 2 cards from hand to activate the scales. Without additional searches, you are left with 3 cards in hand after activating scales on your first turn. Pendulum monsters do not go to the GY, so you can't rely on GY effects. Finally, the deck must mostly consist of pendulum cards for consistency and power (lacks handtraps or traps). Typically, these weaknesses are resolved using pendulum effects. However, Solfachords don't have pendulum effects that resolve these issues.

Heavymetalfoes Electrumite : The best card for Pendulums
Summon Electrumite to use its effect to add Astrograph Sorcerer to the extra deck. Destroy a pendulum card in scale using Electrumite's effect and add Astrograph from the extra deck. Electrumite's effect draws you 1 card and Astrograph uses its effect to summon itself and add a copy of the destroyed pendulum card from the deck. With a single Electrumite you gained a free monster on field with +2 in hand. Electrumite requires two pendulum monsters to summon and you should ideally do the combo before your pend summon. So, how do we get Electrumite on field?

  1. Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser  : It's a free special summon from the pendulum zone if you control no monsters.
  2. Normal Summon Starter : Diviner of the Herald is your main normal summon. You can send Trias Hierarchia to the GY and use its effect to tribute Diviner. Diviner then special summons Cutia from the deck when tributed.

Now that we have Electrumite on field, let's take a look at our Solfachord cards.
Even Scale Solfachords :
8: DoSolfachord Cutia is the main starter of the deck. It can search any of your Solfachord monsters except itself when summoned. By searching Dreamia, you can make Electrumite.
4: SolSolfachord Gracia can search any of your Solfachord spells and traps. Prioritize Harmonia or Elegance.
Odd Scale Solfachords :
7: ReSolfachord Dreamia is an extender that can special summon itself if your have a Solfachord in your pendulum zone.
5: FaSolfachord Fancia is your alternate Solfachord normal summon. It allows you to add any Solfachord monster to your extra deck.
3: LaSolfachord Angelia can special summon a Solfachord monster from your deck that has scales +2/-2 of a monster you tribute. For example, Angelia can tribute itself to special summon Fancia or Coolia from your deck.
1: DoSolfachord Coolia is your main deck boss monster. In your main phase, you can target up to 2 cards and negate their effects until the end of the opponent's turn.
Other Solfachord cards :
Solfachord Harmonia : This is an important field spell that can recover a Solfachord from your extra deck. It can also make any of your Solfachords into a 9 (high) scale.
Solfachord Elegance : This is the most powerful card in Solfachord. It allows you to add any Solfachord from your hand to the extra deck to set your scales. This effect cannot be negated by Ash Blossom.
Solfachord Musica : It allows you to target and destroy a card your opponent controls.

All of the Solfachord Pendulum monsters have pendulum effects that prevent the opponent from negating or reacting to your pendulum summon. This makes the pend summon itself quite resilent. However, what's the payoff?
Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon : When Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon is sent to the GY, you can special summon Vortex Dragon from the extra deck. You can make the 7 rank Xyz using cards like Astrograph Sorcerer and TiSolfachord Beautia.
Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians : For pendulums, having access to a link monster with arrows pointing to your main monster zones is important. You can easily make Selene using the Electrumite and Astrograph Sorcerer you have on field.
Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess : This is the best link 4 that provides plenty of arrows for a pendulum summon. If you have other alternatives, feel free to use those.
The Arrival Cyberse @Ignister : Your main deck Solfachords have fire, earth, water, wind attributes while GranSolfachord Musecia is a light. You can often make a 5000 ATK unaffected boss monster.

*Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring : While not a boss monster, it is vital to stop Maxx "C". Also, it is a level 3 tuner which allows for Halq plays or can help with synchro summoning. Other cards to consider : All of the suggested link monsters are great alternative options as they all have arrows pointing down. Consider using them instead if you already have them.
Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous : You already have an Elder Entity N'tss in case you want to use Diviner's effect. Nadir Servant to add Ecclesia which adds Fleurdelis when special summoned. While this can make your endboard a bit stronger, note that this will prevent you from summoning from the extra deck for the rest of the turn. 

I hope this guide can help new players get into pendulum summoning using my favorite pendulum archetype, Solfachords. There aren't a lot of set plays once you have Electrumite on field, so you have to practice to set up strong fields. The deck hard bricks once every 10 duels, so keep that in mind when adding different engines like Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer to the deck. You can also run a pure, casual Solfachord deck with Solfachord Scale and more main deck Solfachords.

deck_excerpt: An update to my Branded Tearalaments list.
deck_description:
Hi, Grayewick the Fusionist here, and yes I once again uploaded another list of Branded Tearalaments but this one, I think I'm actually convinced and confident with my ratios through testing. Let me discuss the list first and again, I'm only discussing the cards that need explaining in terms of the ratios. For my old list, see https://ygoprodeck.com/branded-tearalaments/ The Main Deck: • The pseudo-starters - The reason why I'm starting with these is because one, they're the starters that you'd normally wouldn't want to Normal Summon. Two, they're the starters that can Special Summon themselves anyway (conditional or not) which saves your Normal Summon. And three, they're either easy access to a Baronne De Fleur and/or hand trap baits for your True Normal Summons. They are:
  1. Visas Starfrost - The Level 6 Tuner of the Deck that gives you access to Baronne De Fleur. He and Tearalaments Shaylen, with a good set of mills can actually potentially lead to full combo. His effect to Special Summon himself destroys a monster as part of the effect, so it triggers all of your Tearalaments monsters and your Despian Tragedy to search.
  2. Tearalaments Shaylen - The other main pseudo-starter/extender for the Deck, which can Special Summon herself during the Main Phase once per turn, then allows you to mill the top 3 cards of your Deck. Her being Level 4 is relevant since she can also give you access to Baronne De Fleur.
  3. Springans Kitt - She's here to mainly search Branded Lost upon getting Normal or Special Summoned, also to recover any of your banished "Branded" Spells/Traps, mainly Branded Retribution. Also, you'd much rather want to see her in your opening hand than Fallen of Albaz, which I've cut down to 1 for this reason.
  4. Tearalaments Meiru - She's the other Normal Summon for Tearalaments, but in this list she's only a one of for the purposes of Fusion climbing to Tearalaments Kaleido-heart.
• The True Normal Summon starters - The reason these two are called "True Normal Summon starters" is because first of all, you most definitely do not want to start off your combo with them most of the time and second, as much as possible, these two are the ones that you'd want to Normal Summon for the following reason(s):
  1. Aluber the Jester of Despia - He's usually gonna be your Branded Opening target, but unlike the pseudo-starters, you'd actually want to Normal Summon him over them. Also this time, you're not gonna be focusing too much on the Branded Fusion search to set up for Mirrorjade, but instead we're almost always going to search for the true star of this list, Despia, Theater of the Branded for one simple reason: Tearalaments Kaleido-heart is a Level 9 Fusion Monster that it can bring back from the GY..
  2. Tearalaments Reinoheart - Him being at 3 have two main reasons: First, is that it's important that we always have access to his name since he's a vital piece to summoning Tearalaments Kaleido-heart and secondly, his effect to Special Summon himself, unlike Aluber, also triggers his effect to send another "Tearalaments" monster to the GY, except a copy of himself. Him getting banished by his own effect isn't actually a detriment since the Branded engine has an excellent grind game and resource recycling when Fusion Summoning because of Lubellion the Searing Dragon and Ad Libitum of Despia.
Spells/Traps • Branded Lost - The reason why I'm playing more of this is because this list has a LOT of effects that Fusion Summon, and you want them to resolve as much as possible. Without it, this list would be significantly weaker and more vulnerable to Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion. • Tearalaments Crime - It's one of your couple of ways of recovering your banished "Tearalaments" monsters, mainly Tearalaments Reinoheart. Final Thoughts Well, it's not really that different to my old Branded Tearalaments list, only did a couple few adjustments but then, that's what testing is for. Also, the fact that Baronne De Fleur can recycle herself to bring out an outed Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon in your GY is just too spicy for me to pass up on. (Also, this one's a bit short because at the time that I was writing this guide, I have a migraine/headache so, yeah.) This was a fun list to test because its crucial weakness is also one of its strengths, the fact that it's heavily reliant on good mills off the top of your Deck to pop off, which makes it also harder to telegraph unless you play the Deck yourself as well. I cannot wait for Tearalaments to get their own dedicated archetypal Fusion Spell. As per usual, if you have any questions or thoughts, feel free to express them down in the comments, which I think is better so that I could deal with more specific concerns if any rather than just generalizing my answers, and I'll respond to them as soon as I possibly can.

deck_excerpt: This is a updated version of my Albaz deck.
deck_description: Pretty much fusion summoning, locking your opponent, and getting rid of their spells or traps.

Credit to u/imperialtrace: https://www.reddit.com/r/yugioh/comments/uklzje/i_went_50_at_locals_with_borrelend_dragon_link/  

Combo 1

Requirements: Chaos Space + Any Light or Dark monster to discard

  1. Activate Chaos Space and search for Collapserpent or Wyverburster

  2. Banish the monster you just discarded to special summon the baby chaos dragon you just searched

  3. Link into Striker Dragon, use effect to search Boot Sector Launch

  4. The baby chaos dragon you used for the link summon also lets you search its counterpart (Collapserpent/Wyverburster)

  5. Banish the dragon in grave to special summon the new one you just searched

  6. Activate the effect of Chaos Space in graveyard, returning the banished baby chaos dragon to your deck to draw 1 card. We will assume this card you just drew is not part of the combo and will be using it as discard fodder.

  7. Link your 2 dragons on the field into Romulus, search for Dragon Ravine

  8. The baby chaos dragon you used for this link summon also lets you search its counterpart

  9. Activate Dragon Ravine and discard a card to dump Absorouter Dragon from deck to grave

  10. Use Absorouter's effect to search for Rokket Tracer

  11. Normal Summon Rokket Tracer

  12. Tracer effect, pop your own Dragon Ravine to special summon Rokket Recharger from deck

  13. Use Recharger to link summon Pisty in the zone to the bottom left of Romulus

  14. Use Romulus and Tracer to Link summon into Quadborrel Dragon above Pisty

  15. Use Pisty effect to revive Tracer underneath Quadborrel

  16. Use Pisty + Tracer to link summon Dillingerous Dragon

  17. Quadborrel effect, discard a card and destroy Dillingerous Dragon

  18. This lets you special summon back Rokket Tracer, Recharger and Dillingerous Dragon with its own effect

  19. Use Quadborrel + Dillingerous + Recharger to Link Summon Borrelend Dragon

  20. Borrelend Dragon effect, targeting the Tracer on field, special summon Recharger from grave

  21. Use Tracer + Recharger to synchro summon Borreload Savage Dragon and equip it with Romulus

Combo 2

Requirements: Starliege Seyfert + Any 2 cards to discard

  1. Normal summon Seyfert, using its effect to send itself to graveyard and search Black Dragon Collapserpent

  2. Special Summon Collapserpernt by banishing Seyfert.

  3. Link summon into Striker Dragon, searching Boot Sector Launch and White Dragon Wyverburster

  4. Special Summon Wyverburster by banishing Collapserpent from grave

  5. Link summon into Romulus, search for Dragon Ravine

  6. Activate Dragon Ravine, discard 1 card to dump Absorouter

  7. Absorouter effect, search Rokket Tracer

  8. Activate Boot Sector Launch, using its effect to special summon Tracer

  9. Tracer effect, pop the Boot Sector and special summon Recharger from deck

  10. Link away Tracer to summon Pisty in the bottom left zone under Romulus

  11. Use Romulus + Recharger to link summon Quadborrel above Pisty

  12. Pisty effect, special summon Tracer

  13. Use Pisty + Tracer to link summon Dillingerous Dragon

  14. Quadborrel effect, discard 1 card to destroy Dillingerous Dragon

  15. Special summon Tracer + Recharger + Dillingerous Dragon

  16. Use Quadborrel + Dillingerous + Recharger to Link Summon Borrelend Dragon

  17. Borrelend Dragon effect, targeting the Tracer on field, special summon Recharger from grave

  18. Use Tracer + Recharger to synchro summon Borreload Savage Dragon and equip it with Romulus

Combo 3

Requirements: Black Metal Dragon + 1 card to discard (or 2 if you choose not to run a second REDMD in your deck)

  1. Summon Black Metal Dragon (normal summon or using One for One)

  2. Link into Striker Dragon, searching Boot Sector Launch and REDMD

  3. Banish Striker to Special Summon REDMD, use its effect to revive Black Metal Dragon

  4. Link both into Dragunity Knight - Romulus, searching Dragon Ravine + another REDMD

  5. Activate Dragon Ravine, pitching the REDMD in hand to send Absorouter to grave

  6. Absorouter effect, search Rokket Tracer to hand

  7. Activate Boot Sector Launch, use effect to special summon Tracer to a zone far away from your Romulus

  8. Tracer effect, destroy your own Boot Sector to search a Rokket Recharger and summon it to a zone away from Romulus (keep the 3 zones below Romulus empty)

  9. Link either Tracer or Recharger into Pisty, put it in the zone to the bottom left of Romulus.

  10. Link Romulus + your other remaining Rokket into Quadborrel Dragon into the extra monster zone where Romulus was.

  11. Pisty is now pointing to the zone below Quadborrel, use Pisty's effect to revive a Tracer or Recharger (doesn't matter).

  12. Use Pisty + the revived Rokket to link into Dillingerous Dragon below Quadborrel.

  13. Activate Quadborrel's effect, pitching a card to destroy your own Dillingerous Dragon

  14. This lets you revive 2 Rokkets (Tracer + Recharger) and the Dillingerous Dragon

  15. Link Quadborrel, Dillingerous and one of the Rokkets into Borrelend Dragon

  16. Use Borrelend Dragon's effect targeting your remaining Rokket and special summon the other Rokket from graveyard.

  17. Tune Rokket Tracer + Recharger and synchro summon Borreload Savage Dragon, equipping Dragunity Knight - Romulus to it.

Starters

  • With these 3 combos in mind, your bread and butter starter cards are Chaos Space, Starliege Seyfert, Black Metal Dragon and One for One (10 total). There's a good chance you'll see at least one of these in your opening hand.

Chain Blocking

  • Linking off Black Metal Dragon into Striker Dragon triggers 2 effects: the BMD search for REDMD and the Striker search for Boot Sector. In most cases, the Boot Sector is going to be more valuable, so you should make Striker chain link 1 and BMD chain link 2, so if they have Ash they can only stop the BMD. Alternatively, if you think REDMD is more important than Boot Sector based on your hand, make the BMD chain link 1 and Striker chain link 2.

  • If you have Noctovision Dragon in hand, you can make that chain link 3 and block your opponent from Ashing Striker or BMD.
